  "prompt": "What are some examples of cardiac muscles?",
  "response": "Cardiac muscles, also known as myocardium, compose the muscular tissue of the heart. Unlike skeletal muscles, which are under voluntary control, cardiac muscles work involuntarily to pump blood throughout the body. Some specific examples of where cardiac muscles function include:\n\n1. **Atrial Myocardium**: The cardiac muscle tissue found in the walls of the atria, the upper chambers of the heart. It helps move blood from the atria to the ventricles.\n\n2. **Ventricular Myocardium**: The muscle tissue within the walls of the ventricles, the lower chambers of the heart. This muscle is responsible for pumping blood out of the heart\u2014deoxygenated blood to the lungs from the right ventricle and oxygenated blood to the rest of the body from the left ventricle.\n\n3. **Papillary Muscles**: These muscles are located in the ventricles of the heart and are attached to the cusps of the atrioventricular valves (the mitral and tricuspid valves) via chordae tendineae. They contract to prevent inversion or prolapse of these valves during ventricular contraction (systole).\n\nOverall, cardiac muscle tissue functions as a deeply interconnected unit to conduct electrical impulses and maintain a consistent, rhythmic heartbeat.",
